<!--
  Protocol: anti-rationalization
  See architecture spec §5.2

  Every agent carries an Excuse -> Rebuttal table. When an agent drafts a
  skip/defer/simplify decision, it checks the table first. If the draft
  matches an excuse pattern, the rebuttal is applied and the decision
  is reconsidered.

  Purpose: catches common rationalization patterns that degrade quality
  over time. Examples of excuses: "this edge case is rare", "good enough
  for now", "we can fix this later", "the test can be skipped".

  Agents declare their Excuse -> Rebuttal rows in the <anti-rationalization>
  block of their agent file (see spec §6.1).

  Invoked by the workflow engine whenever an agent produces a
  skip/defer/simplify decision.

  Status: stub
-->
<protocol id="anti-rationalization" version="0.0.1">
  <status>stub</status>
  <trigger>agent drafts a skip/defer/simplify decision</trigger>
</protocol>
